This diagram visualizes the complex workflow transforming a real-world scene into a digital image.

The pipeline is organized chronologically, moving from physical hardware capture to digital representation.

Optics and sensors initiate the process by converting light radiance into raw analog signals (voltages).

Physical artifacts are introduced here, including lens aberrations, blur, and various sensor noise types.

An Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC) discretizes these signals, implementing crucial sampling and quantization processes.

The mathematical dependencies section shows how optics quality dictates required sampling rates to prevent aliasing.

The output of digitization is linear RAW data, which is usually high bit-depth and mosaiced.

The Image Signal Processor (ISP) then executes a software pipeline to optimize the data for human viewing.

Key ISP steps include demosaicing to reconstruct color and tone mapping to compress dynamic range.

Ultimately, the chart highlights how physical hardware constraints dictate final digital image fidelity and storage needs.
